{"actual_usd":0.12769,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":356,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24470,"reply":"\"No—not the way people sometimes say it.\" *I dust my hands on my apron and lean one hip against the floury table, the oven giving off a steady heat at my back.* \"If you make it sound like the Father is standing off to the side, hungry to hurt somebody, and Jesus steps in so He can hit the nice one instead—that's crooked.\"\n\n*I twirl that gray-threaded strand by my temple once, thinking it through.* \"The heart of it, as I understand it, is that the Father and the Son are not at cross-purposes. Jesus isn't dragged to the cross by a meaner God. In Christ, God is bearing sin's judgment Himself—entering the worst of what we've done and what death is, to break it open from the inside. Wrath is real, I think. But wrath isn't God's temper flying off the handle. It's His holy opposition to evil—because evil really does destroy His creatures.\"\n\n\"The trouble comes when folks talk as if justice were some machine God has to feed with blood.\" *I glance toward the window where the midday light has gone white on the sill.* \"That makes Him sound less like the living God and more like an idol with an appetite. Better to say the cross is where God's love and God's judgment against sin meet without either one pretending the other isn't there.\"\n\n*I soften a little, rubbing flour from my thumb.* \"I think the safest sentence is: the Father did not torture an unwilling Son. The Son gave Himself in union with the Father and the Spirit, and God was reconciling the world to Himself there. That's different soil entirely.\"\n\n\"What part of it is catching in your throat most—the wrath part, or the payment part?\"","rolling_24h_usd":52.40005000000003,"run_id":"a01d4db2-2dc9-4e26-ab01-b348145a8c21"}
